english:
  title: Inscription and Preface for the Temple of Kija
  author: Byeon Gyeyangn
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of Xuande, in the year of Wushen, in the summer, on the fourth month, on the day Jiazi, the King issued a decree, saying: "Long ago, when King Wu of Zhou conquered the Yin dynasty, he enfeoffed the Grand Preceptor of Yin in our land, thus fulfilling his desire to remain unsubmissive to Zhou. Our Eastern realm has matched China in refinement and rites for more than two thousand years, and this we owe entirely to the teachings of Kija. Yet his temple stands cramped and humble, unworthy of reverence. My late father commanded its renovation, and I, inheriting his vision, have overseen its completion. Now it is finished. Let this be inscribed in stone for posterity. Let the court historian compose its record."

    I, your minister Gyeyangn, having received this command, dare not refuse, though trembling with awe.

    I reflect thus: Confucius placed King Wen and Kija side by side in the hexagrams of the Book of Changes, and called them among the "Three Benevolent Ones." Kija's virtue transcends all praise. In ancient times, when Yu tamed the waters and earth, Heaven granted the Great Plan, and proper relationships were established. Yet this teaching never appeared in the records of Yu or Xia dynasties. Only after a thousand years, through Kija, was it revealed. Had Kija not expounded it to King Wu, how would later generations have known of the celestial teachings recorded in the Lo Shu? Is not Kija's contribution to this Way surely no accident? Kija was the teacher of King Wu. That King Wu enfeoffed him not elsewhere but in our Chosŏn meant that our people, morning and night, received his direct influence—the gentlemen heard the essentials of the Great Way, and the common folk tasted the benefits of perfect governance. His influence reached such heights that lost goods were not picked up from the roads. Is this not Heaven's bounty to our Eastern realm, granting us a sage to bless this people? This transcends what human effort alone could achieve.

    The system of the well-fields and the eight ordinances gleam like sun and stars. Our people, generation after generation, have honored his teachings. Even a thousand years hence, they remain as vital as in his own time. With reverent hearts, we naturally cannot help but long for him.

    Our late King Kongjeong was wise and studied antiquity, delighting in the classics and histories. Our present King, blessed with celestial wisdom and sagacity, has cultivated sacred learning. In the Way of the Great Plan's nine categories, he has achieved perfect understanding and harmony of spirit. Through his works and refinements, he fulfills the rites of honoring virtue and repaying merit with utmost sincerity—something no previous monarch could have matched. Let the officials and people rise together to practice these teachings, drawing near to the radiance of the throne and partaking in blessings beyond doubt.

    Ah, how glorious! Buildings have been constructed, fields set aside to provide sacrificial offerings, and households exempted from corvée to maintain the temple grounds. The magistrate has been commanded to oversee the rites with care. The temple stands complete and wanting in nothing.

    I, your minister Gyeyangn, am overwhelmed with gratitude. I bow and kowtow to present this inscription:

    Oh, Kija!
    Follower of King Wen,
    The Great Plan is truth—
    the celestial teaching unfurled.

    Not merely Yin's counselor,
    but Wu's own teacher true.
    Yin abandoned him and fell to ruin;
    Zhou sought him and rose to glory.

    How vast the realm beneath Heaven,
    where safety and peril rest upon one man's shoulders.
    He gathered his virtue and journeyed East—
    Heaven surely favors us.

    Through teaching and governance,
    eight ordinances became law.
    Who remains unenlightened?
    Who stays weak and unbent?

    The Han histories sing his praise:
    'No lost thing lies upon the road.'
    He made the barbarous lands like the civilized;
    Tang honored him with stone.

    Our diligent King
    has restored the broken thread of learning.
    His mind is one with its principles,
    his conduct embodies its way.

    Father founded, son continues—
    the temple stands majestic, soaring high.
    On that lofty hall
    dwells Kija's spirit.

    With each season's offerings,
    we show respect and devotion.
    I, this humble servant,
    have pondered the ancient texts.

    Now receiving the royal command,
    I bow low to write this inscription.
    May his glorious virtue shine
    brightly through ten thousand ages.
  footnotes:
    - King Wu of Zhou defeated the Yin dynasty and enfeoffed Kija, the virtuous minister of Yin, in Chosŏn (ancient Korea) rather than suppress him, allowing him to establish a realm based on the teachings of the Great Plan (Hongbeom).
    - The 'Three Benevolent Ones' (Samin) refers to Wezi, Kija, and Bigan, three worthy ministers of Yin who responded differently to its decline—cited by Confucius as exemplars of virtue.
    - The Great Plan (Hongbeom) is the nine categories of governance recorded in the Book of History, supposedly revealed to Yu the Great and transmitted by Kija to King Wu.
    - The eight ordinances refer to Kija's system of governance, which became foundational to Chosŏn's political and ethical structure.
    - The well-field system (Jeongjeon) was an ancient land distribution method promoting equality and stability, associated with Kija's influence on Korean governance.
    - King Kongjeong was Sejong's grandfather; this inscription was commissioned during Sejong's reign to honor Kija's legacy in Korean civilization.
